#### Non-bilaterian organisms

Asymmetrical and spherical [body shapes](/Body_plan). (a) An organism with an asymmetrical, amoeboid body plan ([Amoeba proteus](/Amoeba_proteus) – an amoeba). (b) An organism with a spherical amoeboid body plan ([Actinophrys sol](/Actinophrys_sol) – a [heliozoan](/Heliozoan)).

For [non-bilaterian](/Non-bilaterian) organisms with variable shapes, like [amoeboid](/Amoeboid) organisms, most directional terms are practically meaningless due to the lack of fixed shape and distinct axes. Similarly, [radially symmetrical](/Radial_symmetry) organisms lack a defined orientation; any arbitrary set of perpendicular axes would be as useful as any other. In these cases, only terms like "superficial" and "deep," or occasionally "proximal" and "distal," remain descriptive.

#### Elongated organisms

Four individuals of [Phaeodactylum tricornutum](/Phaeodactylum_tricornutum), a [diatom](/Diatom) with a fixed elongated shape

Organisms with a fixed, elongated shape allow for at least two directional terms: "longitudinal" along the main axis, and "transverse" across the body. A third axis is often undefined unless a unique structure, like a non-terminal [cytostome](/Cytostome), provides a reference. These are often [planktonic](/Planktonic) [protists](/Protists), viewed in two dimensions under a microscope.

Organisms where the ends of the long axis are distinct ( [Paramecium caudatum](/Paramecium_caudatum), above, and [Stentor roeselii](/Stentor_roeselii), below).

Some elongated [protists](/Protists) have clearly defined ends. The end with a mouth (or equivalent, like the [cytostome](/Cytostome) in [Paramecium](/Paramecium) or [Stentor](/Stentor_(ciliate))), or the end typically leading in [locomotion](/Animal_locomotion) (like the [flagellum](/Flagellum) end of [Euglena](/Euglena)), is usually designated as anterior. The opposite end is then posterior.&#91;60&#93; This terminology technically applies to organisms that are always [planktonic](/Planktonic), though it can be extended to [sessile](/Sessility_(zoology)) ones.&#91;61&#93;

A cluster of Euplectella aspergillum sponges (Venus flower baskets), showing the apical–basal axes

Organisms attached to a [substrate](/Substrate_(biology)), such as [sponges](/Porifera) and [animal-like protists](/Protista), also have distinct ends. The attachment point is the basal end (from [Latin](/Latin_language) *basis*, meaning 'support/foundation'), while the furthest end is the apical end (from [Latin](/Latin_language) *apex*, meaning 'peak/tip').

#### Radially symmetrical organisms

[Radially symmetrical organisms](/Radial_symmetry) include the [Cnidarians](/Cnidaria) ([jellyfish](/Jellyfish), [sea anemones](/Sea_anemones), [corals](/Corals)) and [comb jellies](/Ctenophora).&#91;62&#93; Adult [echinoderms](/Echinodermata) like [starfish](/Starfish) and [sea urchins](/Sea_urchin), with their five-part symmetry, are also included.&#91;63&#93; Echinoderm [larvae](/Larva), however, are [bilaterally symmetrical](/Symmetry_in_biology).&#91;63&#93;

Cnidarians have a mouth at one end, the oral end (from [Latin](/Latin_language) *ōrālis*, meaning 'of the mouth'), and no opening at the opposite aboral end.&#91;62&#93; They are radially symmetric around the oral-aboral axis.&#91;62&#93; With only this single defined axis, terms like "lateral," "dorsal," and "ventral" are meaningless, replaced by the generic term "peripheral" (from [Ancient Greek](/Ancient_Greek_language) *periphereia*, meaning 'circumference'). "Medial" can be used, but in radiates, it refers to the central point rather than a central axis as in vertebrates. Thus, multiple radial and medio-peripheral axes are possible.&#91;64&#93;

Comb jellies exhibit biradial symmetry about two planes: a tentacular plane and a pharyngeal plane.&#91;65&#93;

*   [Aurelia aurita](/Aurelia_aurita), another species of [jellyfish](/Jellyfish), showing multiple radial and medio-peripheral axes.
*   The [sea star](/Sea_star) [Porania pulvillus](/Porania_pulvillus), showing aboral and oral surfaces.

#### Spiders

*   See also: [Glossary of spider terms](/Glossary_of_spider_terms) and [Spider anatomy](/Spider_anatomy)

Specialized terms are used for [spiders](/Spiders). For example, "prolateral" and "retrolateral" describe surfaces of a spider's leg. Prolateral refers to the surface closest to the anterior end of the body, while retrolateral is closest to the posterior end.&#91;66&#93; Spiders typically have eight eyes arranged in four pairs on the [carapace](/Carapace) of the [prosoma](/Prosoma). The size, shape, and location of these eyes are characteristic of different spider families.&#91;67&#93; They are usually arranged in two horizontal, symmetrical rows, designated as anterior and posterior lateral eyes (ALE and PLE), and anterior and posterior median eyes (AME and PME).&#91;67&#93;

*   Aspects of spider anatomy. This aspect shows the mainly prolateral surface of the anterior femora, plus the typical horizontal eye pattern of the [Sparassidae](/Sparassidae).
*   Typical arrangement of eyes in the [Lycosidae](/Lycosidae), with PME being the largest.
*   In the [Salticidae](/Salticidae), the AME are the largest.

